<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Increment Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Increments mission counters by a configured amount. Used with Counter trigger logic to build multi-step objectives, kill counts, collection counts, progress gates, and conditional mission flow.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Increment Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Increment</Bold> Event Point increases one of the mission counters by a value chosen
        by the mission creator.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        These are the same counters used by the <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger guard in the Trigger
        Settings section. The Increment Event Point changes a counter. The Counter trigger watches a
        counter and fires when that counter reaches a required threshold.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This makes Increment useful for building mission logic such as “kill two enemies,” “collect
        three items,” “visit all checkpoints,” “destroy all targets,” or “complete several separate
        steps before the next objective starts.”
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_increment_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Simple summary:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Increment adds a value to a counter. A separate Event Point using the Counter trigger can watch that counter and fire once the counter reaches a threshold.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding an Increment Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select <Bold>Increment</Bold> from the Event
        Point type list, and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window opens with the standard common properties, trigger
        settings, and the Increment-specific fields.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_increment_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Increment uses the normal Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type,
        letter group, colour, position, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The position of an Increment Event Point is usually not gameplay-critical because it does not
        place a physical object in the world. The important parts are the counter it modifies, the
        amount it adds, and the trigger that causes the increment to happen.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Even though the position is not usually important, it is still helpful to place Increment
        Event Points near the related objective, NPC, item, or logic area so the mission remains easy
        to understand later.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_increment_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Increment Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Increment has two type-specific properties:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Counter Index</Bold> — which mission counter should be changed.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Increment By</Bold> — how much should be added to that counter when this Event
                Point fires.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_increment_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Counter Index
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Counter Index</Bold> specifies which counter this Increment Event Point modifies.
        Missions can use multiple counters. In practice, counters are usually referred to by index
        number, commonly <Bold>0–9</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Counter Index is critical because it must match the counter being watched elsewhere by a
        <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger. If Increment modifies counter 6, but the Counter trigger is
        watching counter 4, the trigger will not fire from this increment.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical Counter Index detail:</Run>
                <Run>
                    The Counter Index on the Increment Event Point must match the Counter Index used by the Counter trigger that is waiting for the threshold.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Increment By
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Increment By</Bold> controls how much is added to the selected counter when the Event
        Point fires.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Most simple setups increment by <Bold>1</Bold>. For example, each defeated enemy may add 1 to
        a kill counter. However, the increment does not have to be 1. You can increment by a larger
        amount if a task should count for more progress.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For example, a difficult enemy could increment a counter by 2, while a normal enemy increments
        by 1. A major objective could increment by 5 if the threshold is designed around weighted
        progress.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Increment Works with Counter Triggers
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Increment and Counter trigger logic are two separate pieces of the same system.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Increment Event Point:
    Adds value to counter X.

Counter Trigger:
    Watches counter X.
    Fires when counter X reaches threshold Y.
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        A Counter trigger normally has two important parameters:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Counter Index Number</Bold> — which counter the trigger is watching.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Threshold</Bold> — the counter value required before the trigger fires.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        All counters start at <Bold>0</Bold>. If a Counter trigger watches counter 6 with threshold 2,
        then it will fire once counter 6 has been incremented to 2 or higher.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_increment_counter_trigger.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Mental model:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Increment is the thing that changes the number. Counter trigger is the thing that reacts when the number is high enough.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Settings for Increment
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Increment Event Point also needs its own trigger. This trigger decides when the counter
        should be increased.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Common Increment trigger examples include:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Killed or Arrested</Bold> — increment when a target NPC is killed or arrested.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Killed Not Arrested</Bold> — increment only when a target NPC is killed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Person Arrested</Bold> — increment when a target NPC is arrested.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Item Held</Bold> or <Bold>Specific Item Held</Bold> — increment when the player has a required item.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Enters Radius</Bold> — increment when the player reaches a checkpoint.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> — increment after another Event Point has fired.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Conversation Finished</Bold> — increment after a conversation completes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Switch</Bold> or <Bold>Player Uses in Radius</Bold> — increment when the player uses something.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_increment_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Do not forget:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Increment has its own trigger. The counter only changes when the Increment Event Point fires.
                    Setting Counter Index and Increment By is not enough by itself.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Example: Trigger a Message After Two Enemies Are Killed
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        This example uses counter 6 to track whether two enemy NPCs have been killed. Once both are
        dead, a congratulation message fires.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_increment_two_enemy_example.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        High-Level Logic
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Enemy 1 killed -&gt; Increment counter 6 by 1
Enemy 2 killed -&gt; Increment counter 6 by 1

Counter 6 reaches threshold 2 -&gt; Message fires
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        Since all counters start at 0, counter 6 reaches 2 only after both increments have happened.
        The message Event Point can then be triggered by a Simple Waypoint or other logic node that
        uses the Counter trigger.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Step-by-Step Setup
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create two enemy NPC Event Points.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create one Increment Event Point for the first enemy.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the first Increment Event Point to <Bold>Counter Index = 6</Bold> and <Bold>Increment By = 1</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the first Increment Event Point trigger to fire when enemy 1 is killed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create another Increment Event Point for the second enemy.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the second Increment Event Point to <Bold>Counter Index = 6</Bold> and <Bold>Increment By = 1</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the second Increment Event Point trigger to fire when enemy 2 is killed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create a Simple Waypoint or logic Event Point that uses the <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set that Counter trigger to <Bold>Counter Index = 6</Bold> and <Bold>Threshold = 2</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Trigger the congratulation message from that Counter-triggered logic Event Point, usually through a dependency.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the mission by killing each enemy and confirming the message appears only after both are dead.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Design note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    You can increment by more than 1. A harder enemy could increment by 2, or a major objective could increment by a larger amount if your threshold is designed around weighted progress.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Uses
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Kill or Arrest Counts</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Increment a counter each time a required enemy is killed or arrested. A Counter trigger can
        then fire when enough enemies have been dealt with.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Collection Objectives</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Increment a counter each time the player collects or obtains a required item. Fire the next
        objective when the collection threshold is reached.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Checkpoint Progress</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Increment a counter when the player reaches each checkpoint. Use the Counter trigger to detect
        when all required checkpoints have been visited.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Multi-Part Objective Completion</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Increment the same counter from several different tasks. When the total reaches the required
        threshold, unlock the next part of the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Weighted Progress</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use different Increment By values to make some tasks count more than others. For example, a
        hard enemy might count as 2 progress points while a normal enemy counts as 1.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Increment Workflow
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide what progress you want to track.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a counter index, such as counter 6.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create an Increment Event Point for each action that should add progress.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set each Increment Event Point to the same <Bold>Counter Index</Bold> if they are contributing to the same objective.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Increment By</Bold> to the amount each action should add.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set each Increment Event Point’s trigger so it fires when the relevant action occurs.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create another Event Point that uses the <Bold>Counter</Bold> trigger guard.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the Counter trigger to watch the same <Bold>Counter Index</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the Counter trigger <Bold>Threshold</Bold> to the required total.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use that Counter-triggered Event Point to start the next objective, message, win condition, reward, or mission event.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test every way the counter can be incremented.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Troubleshooting
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The counter-triggered event never fires</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Increment Event Points are actually triggering.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Increment Event Points use the same Counter Index as the Counter trigger.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the threshold is reachable from the total increments.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Counter trigger is on the Event Point that should respond to the counter reaching the threshold.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test with a lower threshold to confirm the logic chain works.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The event fires too early</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether the threshold is too low.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether an Increment Event Point is firing more than once.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether Increment By is larger than expected.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether another Event Point is also incrementing the same Counter Index.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The wrong objective progresses</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the Counter Index on every Increment Event Point involved.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the Counter Index on every Counter trigger.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Make sure different objectives are not accidentally sharing the same counter index.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use consistent colours, groups, or notes to keep counter logic organised.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">An enemy death does not increment the counter</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Increment Event Point trigger references the correct NPC Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check whether the trigger should be <Bold>Killed or Arrested</Bold>, <Bold>Killed Not Arrested</Bold>, or <Bold>Person Arrested</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the NPC actually reaches the trigger condition during gameplay.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Increment is powerful because it lets multiple independent actions contribute to one shared mission condition.
                    Keep counter indexes organised and always make sure the Increment and Counter trigger are using the same counter.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>